# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: camden-new-jersey
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] "**100% Pure Love**" is a song by American singer-songwriter Crystal Waters from her second studio album, *Storyteller* (1994).
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] It was released on April 11, 1994, by Mercury Records as the album's lead single.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] The song was written by Waters with Basement Boys, who produced it, and became a worldwide hit.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] It reached the top 20 in Australia, Finland, the Netherlands, Switzerland, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] The single is certified platinum in Australia and gold in the US.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] In 1995, it was awarded the prize for Top ASCAP Dance Song.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] The accompanying music video, directed by Marcus Nispel, was nominated for Best Dance Video at both the 1994 MTV Video Music Awards and the 1994 *Billboard* Music Video Awards.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] The song is inspired by her relationship at the time.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] The singer says she chose the stylings of the song as a reaction to the popularity of gangsta rap during the mid-1990s in the United States.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] "From the back to the middle and around again, I'm going to be there 'til the end, 100% pure love" emerged in the next draft and became the lyrics in the completed version of the song.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] Crystal Waters also signed and debuted as a model with the Ford Modeling Agency in August 1994.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] They included her as a special guest in fashion collections in both Europe and the United States.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] "100% Pure Love" was the theme of Ford's “Supermodel of the World" contest that year.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] Larry Flick from *Billboard* magazine wrote that here, the "enigmatic voice" behind the 1991 smash "Gypsy Woman" "returns with a percussive pop/dance twirler from her new *Storyteller* opus.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] Though it seemed impossible to come up with a hook as catchy as '*la-da-di, la-di-da*', Waters and cohorts the Basement Boys have done exactly that, and wrapped it with dramatic strings and butt shagging cowbells." M.R.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] Martinez from *Cash Box* felt that Waters' "smokey vocals" worked best on uptempo material, like "100% Pure Love".
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] Anderson Jones from *Entertainment Weekly* stated that the "hip-swaying infectious grooves" of the track "can't be denied." Bradley Stern from *Idolator* noted that it is "armed with a real subtle earworm of a chorus", calling it a "campy house anthem".
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] In his weekly UK chart commentary, James Masterton wrote, "The lady with possibly the most unusual voice in dance music is back." He also described the song as "more of the same kind of left-field nonsense".
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] A breezy backdrop to a drunken evening in an Ibiza/Essex discotheque." Orla Swift from *Record-Journal* deemed it a "bright, dynamic number", that is "displaying a knack both for catchy melodies and innovative arrangements".
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] Tim Jeffery from the *Record Mirror* Dance Update noted that it "features a catchy 'Back to the middle and round again' hook that should be enough to propel it into the charts." In his weekly *Record Mirror* dance column, James Hamilton named it a "catchily chorused jiggly chugger".
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] Jonathan Bernstein from *Spin* viewed it as a "potential successor" to Waters' signature singles.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] Allen Jr. from *Toledo Blade* considered it the "most forceful" of the dance singles on the album.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] The single reached number 11 on the US *Billboard* Hot 100, number one on the *Billboard* Dance Club Play chart, and number 38 on the *Billboard* Hot R&B Singles chart.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] It spent a total of 45 weeks on the *Billboard* Hot 100 chart, becoming one of the longest-charting singles in the US.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] The song won a *Billboard* Music Award for Top-Selling Hot Dance Music Club Play Single at the 1994 *Billboard* Music Awards.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] The song was certified gold in the United States.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] In Europe, it entered the top 20 in Finland, the Netherlands, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] In the UK, the single peaked at number 15 during its second week on the UK Singles Chart, on April 24.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] On the *Music Week* Dance Singles chart, it reached number one.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] Additionally, it was a top-30 hit in Austria and Iceland and a top-40 hit in Belgium and Germany.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] On the Eurochart Hot 100, "100% Pure Love" reached number 49, and it also topped the European Dance Radio Chart.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] The song proved to be most popular in Australia.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] It first entered the ARIA Singles Chart at number 40 on June 26, 1994, then reached number three three weeks later.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] On July 31, the song reached its peak position of number two.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] It dropped to number three the next week, then spent four more weeks at that position before falling to number four on September 11.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] Afterwards, it remained in the chart for a further seven weeks before dropping out of the top 50 on November 6.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] It finished 1994 as Australia's 11th-best-selling single and has since received a platinum certification from the Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) for shipments exceeding 70,000 copies.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] The music video for "100% Pure Love" was directed by German director Marcus Nispel.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] The choreography was done by then-unknown Michael K.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] The video was nominated for Best Dance Video at the 1994 MTV Video Music Awards and for Best Clip of the Year in the category for Dance at the 1994 *Billboard* Music Video Awards.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] In Europe, it was put on "break out" rotation on MTV Europe in June 1994.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] One month later, the video was B-listed on France's MCM and Germany's VIVA.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] "100% Pure Love" was later made available remastered in HD by Vevo on YouTube in 2009, having generated more than 36 million views as of late 2025.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] ASCAP awarded "100% Pure Love" the prize for Top ASCAP Dance Song in 1995.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] Australian music channel Max included it in their list of the "1000 Greatest Songs of All Time" in 2011.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] Idolator ranked it one of "The 50 Best Pop Singles of 1994" in 2014.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] Matt Stopera and Brian Galindo of *BuzzFeed* ranked it number nine in their list of "The 101 Greatest Dance Songs of the '90s" in 2017.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] In 2021, the same publication ranked it number five in their list of "The 50 Best '90s Songs of Summer", naming it "the greatest '90s dance song of the '90s dance genre".
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] *Billboard* magazine ranked "100% Pure Love" number 500 in their list of the "Top Songs of the '90s" in 2019 and number 81 in "The 100 Greatest LGBTQ+ Anthems of All Time" in 2025.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] British band Years & Years released a cover of the song in 2022 that Target would use for its holiday campaign that year.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] On November 1, 2022, Olly Alexander-helmed Years & Years released a cover of the song.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] In December 2023, actress and singer Keke Palmer teamed up with search engine Google to promote black-owned businesses with a modified cover of Crystal Waters' 100% Pure Love titled for the occasion “100% Black Owned”.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] A music video was shot for the occasion with appearance and vocals by Crystal Waters.
[src:camden-new-jersey/100-pure-love] The performance promoted a new search engine highlighting small black owned businesses on the internet.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The **119th United States Congress** is the current meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] It convened on January 3, 2025, for the last 17 days of Joe Biden's presidency and continued during the first two years of Donald Trump's second presidency.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Following the 2024 elections, the Republican Party retained its slim majority in the House of Representatives (albeit with losing two net seats to end up with a three-seat majority).
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The Republican Party also won a three-seat majority in the Senate after winning four net seats.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Upon Trump's second inauguration on January 20, 2025, the Republican Party has an overall federal government trifecta for the first time since the 115th Congress (2017–2019), which was in session during Trump's first term.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The 119th Congress features the slimmest majority in the House for any party since the 72nd Congress (1931–1933), and the first openly transgender member of Congress in history, Representative Sarah McBride (D-DE).
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] It also features the fewest split Senate delegations since the passage of the Seventeenth Amendment, which established the direct election of U.S. senators.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Despite a trifecta, the first year of the Congress saw the lowest number of House votes in a nonelection year since the 101st Congress in 1990.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] In the 2024 elections, the Republican Party retained control of the House of Representatives and gained control of the Senate, while Republican nominee Donald Trump won the presidential election, securing a second non-consecutive term.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The results of the election were attributed to economic conditions of voters and concerns over immigration, particularly the Mexico–United States border crisis.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The Senate flipped to a 53–47 Republican majority, and in their leadership elections, Senator John Thune of South Dakota was elected to succeed Mitch McConnell, who had been in power for 18 years.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The House assumed a 220–215 Republican majority, among the narrowest controlling majorities in House history with the 65th Congress.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Mike Johnson was re-elected as speaker on the first ballot after initially not receiving enough votes on the roll call, with the vote remaining open until enough members changed votes to support him.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] On January 6, a joint session convened to count the presidential Electoral College votes.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The proceedings were peaceful, four years after the January 6 Capitol attack, in which supporters of Trump entered the Capitol and disrupted Joe Biden's certification as president.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] In response to the attack and Trump's efforts to overturn the 2020 election, Congress has passed revisions to the Electoral Count Act that prevent the vice president from altering the results and significantly raises the bar for certification objections.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The numbers refer to their Senate classes.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] All class 1 seats were contested in the November 2024 elections.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] In this Congress, class 1 means their term commenced in the current Congress, requiring re-election in 2030; class 2 means their term ends with this Congress, requiring re-election in 2026; and class 3 means their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 2028.
[src:camden-new-jersey/119th-united-states-congress-p01] All seats were filled by election in November 2024, or special elections thereafter as noted below.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The film was theatrically released in the United States on December 29, 1995, by Universal Pictures.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] It received positive reviews from critics and grossed over $168.8 million worldwide against a $29 million budget.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] At the 68th Academy Awards, the film was nominated for Best Supporting Actor (for Pitt) and Best Costume Design.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] It garnered seven nominations at the 22nd Saturn Awards, winning three: Best Science Fiction Film, Best Supporting Actor, and Best Costumes.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Pitt also won Best Supporting Actor at the 53rd Golden Globe Awards.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] In 2035, twenty-nine years after a virus killed 99 percent of the global human population, James Cole is a prisoner in a compound underneath the ruins of Philadelphia.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] He is selected by scientists for a mission to travel to 1996 and collect information on the original strain of the virus so a cure can be developed.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Cole experiences recurring dreams of a childhood experience in which he saw a man being shot in an airport terminal.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Upon being sent back in time, Cole arrives in Baltimore in 1990, not 1996 as planned.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] He is arrested and committed to a psychiatric hospital on the diagnosis of Dr.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] He encounters fellow inmate Jeffrey Goines, an outspoken critic of consumerism.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Cole tells the hospital doctors he is searching for the Army of the Twelve Monkeys, the group that unleashed the virus in 1996, which is the past.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] During an escape attempt aided by Jeffrey, Cole is abruptly returned to the future.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The scientists attempt to send Cole back to 1996, but he briefly arrives on a World War I battlefield, where he encounters José, another inmate from the future, before being shot in the leg.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] In 1996, Railly gives a lecture on the Cassandra Complex where she briefly encounters Dr.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Peters, who mentions the destruction of the environment by humanity.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] She is kidnapped in her car and told to drive to Philadelphia.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Railly offers him medical help and extracts the bullet from his leg.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] His investigation leads them to Jeffrey, which they discover is the leader of the Army of the Twelve Monkeys and the son of renowned virologist Dr.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Cole is abruptly returned to the future.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Railly is told by police that the bullet from Cole's leg was from before the 1920s, which prompts her to identify Cole in a battlefield photograph from World War I that she's gathered during her research.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] She urges Leland to secure his lab against access by his son.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Leland shares his intention to improve the lab's security with his assistant, Dr.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Cole arrives in 1996 again and finds Railly.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] He tells her he believes himself delusional, while she says she's not sure any more.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Railly leaves a voicemail on a number Cole says was given to him by the scientists.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Cole tells her he has already heard her message, played to him by the scientists in the future.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Cole and Railly decide to spend the following days together at the Florida Keys.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] On their way there, they learn that the Army of the Twelve Monkeys is an animal rights organization led by Jeffrey, and their graffiti "we did it" refers to liberating animals from the Philadelphia Zoo, not releasing the virus.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] At the airport, Cole records a message on the voicemail number, saying the Army of the Twelve Monkeys is a false lead and that he's not coming back.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Peters at the airport and recognizes him through a newspaper photo alongside Leland.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Cole comes across José, who tracked him down after his last message, and hands him a gun.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Railly informs Cole of Peters, and Cole attempts to shoot him, but is shot dead by police.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] As Cole dies in Railly's arms, she makes eye contact with a young boy witnessing the scene.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Peters boards his flight and takes a seat beside Jones, one of the scientists who orchestrated Cole's mission.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Outside the airport, the young boy who observed the shooting, James, watches the airplane take off.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The genesis of *12 Monkeys* came from executive producer Robert Kosberg, who had been a fan of the French short film *La Jetée* (1962).
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Kosberg persuaded that film's director, Chris Marker, to let him pitch the project to Universal Pictures, seeing it as a perfect basis for a full-length science fiction film.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Universal agreed to purchase the remake rights and hired David and Janet Peoples to write the screenplay.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Producer Charles Roven chose Terry Gilliam to direct, because he believed the filmmaker's style was perfect for *12 Monkeys*' nonlinear storyline and time travel subplot.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Gilliam had just abandoned a film adaptation of *A Tale of Two Cities* when he signed to direct *12 Monkeys*, though Gilliam felt the script was "too complex" to take on.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The film represents the second film for which Gilliam did not write or co-write the screenplay.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Although he prefers to direct his own scripts, he was captivated by Peoples' "intriguing and intelligent script.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] It deals with time, madness and a perception of what the world is or isn't.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] It is a study of madness and dreams, of death and re-birth, set in a world coming apart".
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Universal took longer than expected to approve *12 Monkeys*, although Gilliam had two stars (Willis and Pitt) and a firm budget of $29.5 million (low for a Hollywood science fiction film).
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Universal's production of *Waterworld* (1995) had resulted in various cost overruns.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] To get *12 Monkeys* approved for production, Gilliam persuaded Willis to lower his normal asking price.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Because of Universal's strict production incentives and his history with the studio on *Brazil*, Gilliam received final cut privilege.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The Writers Guild of America was skeptical of the "inspired by" credit for *La Jetée* and Chris Marker.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Gilliam said that he had not seen *La Jetée* when he made *12 Monkeys*.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Gilliam's initial casting choices were Nick Nolte as James Cole and Jeff Bridges as Jeffrey Goines, but Universal objected.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Other actors were suggested for the roles included Nicolas Cage and Tom Cruise, but Gilliam rejected the choices.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Gilliam, who first met Bruce Willis while casting Jeff Bridges' role in *The Fisher King* (1991), believed Willis evoked Cole's characterization as being "somebody who is strong and dangerous but also vulnerable".
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Gilliam later stated that he wasn't originally interested in casting Willis because of the actor's mouth.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Kathryn Railly because he was impressed by her performance in *Blink* (1994).
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The director first met Stowe when he was casting his abandoned film adaptation of *A Tale of Two Cities*.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] "She has this incredible ethereal beauty and she's incredibly intelligent", Gilliam said of Stowe.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Gilliam originally believed that Pitt was not right for the role of Jeffrey Goines, but the casting director convinced him otherwise.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Pitt was cast for a comparatively small salary, as he was still relatively unknown at the time.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] By the time of *12 Monkeys*' release, *Interview with the Vampire* (1994), *Legends of the Fall* (1994), and *Se7en* (1995) had been released, making Pitt an A-list actor, which drew greater attention to the film and boosted its box-office standing.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] In Philadelphia, months before filming, Pitt spent weeks at Temple University's hospital, visiting and studying the psychiatric ward to prepare for his role.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Principal photography lasted from February 8 to May 6, 1995.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Shooting on location in Philadelphia and Baltimore (including the Senator Theatre) in winter was fraught with weather problems.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] There were also technical glitches with the futuristic mechanical props.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Because the film has a nonlinear storyline, continuity errors occurred, and some scenes had to be reshot.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Gilliam also injured himself when he went horseback riding.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Despite setbacks, the director managed to stay within the budget and was only a week behind his shooting schedule.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] "It was a tough shoot", acknowledged Jeffrey Beecroft, the film's production designer.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] "There wasn't a lot of money or enough time.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Terry is a perfectionist, but he was really adamant about not going over budget.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The filmmakers were not allowed access to sound stages; thus, they had to find abandoned buildings or landmarks to use.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The exteriors of the climactic airport scene were shot at the Baltimore–Washington International Airport, while the interior scenes were shot at the Pennsylvania Convention Center (formerly Reading Terminal).
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Filming at the psychiatric hospital was done at the Eastern State Penitentiary and Girard College.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Some shots took place in abandoned motels in Camden, New Jersey.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] *12 Monkeys* was shot in the 1.85:1 format rather than anamorphic.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Gilliam used the same filmmaking style as he had in *Brazil* (1985), including the art direction and cinematography (specifically using Fresnel lenses).
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The appearance of the interrogation room where Cole is being interviewed by the scientists was based on the work of Lebbeus Woods; these scenes were shot at three power stations (two in Philadelphia and one in Baltimore).
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Gilliam intended to show Cole being interviewed through a multi-screen interrogation TV set because he felt the machinery evoked a "nightmarish intervention of technology.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] You try to see the faces on the screens in front of you, but the real faces and voices are down there and you have these tiny voices in your ear.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] To me that's the world we live in, the way we communicate these days, through technical devices that pretend to be about communication but may not be".
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The art department made sure that the 2035 underground world only used pre-1996 technology, to depict the bleakness of the future.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Gilliam, Beecroft and set decorator Crispian Sallis went to several flea markets and salvage warehouses looking for materials to decorate the sets.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The majority of visual effects sequences were created by Peerless Camera Company, which Gilliam founded in the late 1970s with Kent Houston, the film's visual effects supervisor.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Additional digital compositing was done by The Mill, while Cinesite provided film scanning services.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The film's score was composed, arranged, and conducted by English musician Paul Buckmaster.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The main theme is based on Argentine tango musician/composer Astor Piazzolla's *Suite Punta del Este*.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Universal Pictures released *12 Monkeys* on VHS on January 28, 1997.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] It was first released on DVD on March 31, 1998, containing the same extras as the LaserDisc.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] It was re-released as a Special Edition DVD on May 10, 2005, with a new transfer of the film and identical extras.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] It was also released on HD DVD on March 4, 2008, with the same extras.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] It was released on Blu-ray Disc on July 28, 2009, with the same extras.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Arrow Films released a new Blu-ray of the film on October 15, 2018, containing a new transfer of the film, remastered in 4K from the original negative, all of the previous extras, as well as a vintage 1996 interview with Terry Gilliam, and an interview with Gilliam scholar Ian Christie.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Throughout the film, Cole is brought into an interrogation room and told to sit in a chair attached to a vertical rail on the wall.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] A spherical machine with screens of varying sizes showing close-ups of the faces of the scientists interrogating Cole, supported by a metal armature is suspended directly in front of him, probing for weaknesses as the inquisitors interrogate him.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Architect Lebbeus Woods filed a lawsuit against Universal in February 1996, claiming that his work "Neomechanical Tower (Upper) Chamber" was used without permission.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Woods won his lawsuit, requiring Universal to remove the scenes, but he ultimately allowed their inclusion in exchange for a "high six-figure cash settlement" from Universal.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] After the release of *The Zero Theorem* in 2013, claims were made that Gilliam had meant it as part of a trilogy.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] I don't know who started it but once it started it never stopped".
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] On the review aggregator website Rotten Tomatoes, 88% of 73 critics' reviews are positive, with an average rating of 7.6/10.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Metacritic, which uses a weighted average, assigned the film a score of 74 out of 100, based on 20 critics, indicating "generally favorable" reviews.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Audiences polled by CinemaScore gave the film an average grade of "B" on an A+ to F scale.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Roger Ebert found *12 Monkeys*' depiction of the future similar to *Blade Runner* (1982, also scripted by David Peoples) and *Brazil* (1985, also directed by Terry Gilliam).
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] "The film is a celebration of madness and doom, with a hero who tries to prevail against the chaos of his condition, and is inadequate", Ebert wrote.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] "This vision is a cold, dark, damp one, and even the romance between Willis and Stowe feels desperate rather than joyous.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The film's hero fears that he's half-crazy, and for two hours Mr.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Gilliam artfully keeps his audience feeling the same way." Desson Thomson of *The Washington Post* praised the art direction and set design.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] "Willis and Pitt's performances, Gilliam's atmospherics and an exhilarating momentum easily outweigh such trifling flaws in the script", Thomson wrote.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Peter Travers from *Rolling Stone* magazine attributes the film's success to Gilliam's direction and Willis' performance.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Internet reviewer James Berardinelli believed the filmmakers had an intelligent and creative motive for the time-travel subplot.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Rather than being sent to change the past, James Cole is instead observing it to make a better future.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Richard Corliss of *Time* magazine felt the film's time-travel aspect and apocalyptic depiction of a bleak future were clichés.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] "In its frantic mix of chaos, carnage and zoo animals, *12 Monkeys* is *Jumanji* for adults", Corliss wrote.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Brad Pitt was nominated for the Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor, but lost to Kevin Spacey for *The Usual Suspects*.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Julie Weiss was also nominated for the Academy Award for Best Costume Design, but lost to James Acheson for *Restoration*.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] However, Pitt won the Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor in a Motion Picture.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Terry Gilliam was honored for his direction at the 46th Berlin International Film Festival.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The film also received positive notices from the science fiction community.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] It was nominated for the Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation and the Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy and Horror Films awarded it the Saturn Award for Best Science Fiction Film at the 22nd Saturn Awards.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Pitt and Weiss won awards at the ceremony as well; Gilliam, Bruce Willis, Madeleine Stowe, and writers David and Janet Peoples also received nominations.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] On August 26, 2013, *Entertainment Weekly* announced that Syfy was developing a *12 Monkeys* television series based on the film.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The pilot was written by Terry Matalas and Travis Fickett, who had previously written for the series *Terra Nova*.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Due to the series being labeled as "cast contingent", the series did not move forward until the roles of Cole and Goines were cast.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] In April 2014, Syfy green-lit the first season, which consisted of 13 episodes, including the pilot filmed in 2013.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The series premiered on January 16, 2015.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] On March 12, 2015, the series was renewed for a second season that began airing in April 2016.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] Actress Madeleine Stowe made an appearance in one Season 2 episode, being the only cast member of the film to appear on the series.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] On June 29, 2016, the series was renewed for a 10-episode third season, set to premiere in 2017.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The third season aired over three consecutive nights, from May 19 to May 21, 2017.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] A fourth and final season was announced on March 16, 2017.
[src:camden-new-jersey/12-monkeys] The eleven-episode fourth season ran from June 15 to July 6, 2018.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:camden-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:camden-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:camden-new-jersey/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The initial growth of Camden industrially is often credited to the "big three" employers: RCA Victor, Campbell's Soup Company and New York Shipbuilding Corporation.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The "big three" felt compelled to move away from Camden in the mid-to-late-20th century as they could find cheaper workers elsewhere.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Though the city has declined in recent decades since the decline of heavy industry in the area and white flight to the suburbs, the city has made efforts to revitalize itself through various infrastructure and community projects.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Projects such as the redevelopment of the waterfront area brought three tourist attractions to the area: the Battleship New Jersey Museum and Memorial, the Freedom Mortgage Pavilion and the Adventure Aquarium.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The city is the home of Rutgers University–Camden, which was founded as the South Jersey Law School in 1926, and Cooper Medical School of Rowan University, which opened in 2012.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden also houses both Cooper University Hospital and Virtua Our Lady of Lourdes Hospital.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden County College and Rowan University also have campuses in downtown Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The "eds and meds" institutions account for roughly 45% of Camden's total employment.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Once known for violent crime, the restructuring of the police force in 2013 has been credited for its decline.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] As of January 2021, violent crime was down 46% from its high in the 1990s and at the lowest level since the 1960s.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Overall crime reports in 2020 were down 74% compared to 1974, the first year of uniform crime-reporting in the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The city traces back to local indigenous Lenape, who are believed to have inhabited this area 13–15,000 years prior to the first European settlers.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Between 1623 and 1627, Captain Cornelius Jacobsen May, an officer with the Dutch West India Company and first director of New Netherland, established Fort Nassau, where the Delaware River meets Big Timber Creek, which is today known as Brooklawn.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 1633, David Pietersen De Vries, a Dutch commander, was sailing up the Delaware River when he came across Natives in control of the fort.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The settlers that had been left at the fort had decided to return to New Amsterdam (*Today* Manhattan, New York).
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Wouter van Twiller, Governor of New Netherland, restored Fort Nassau.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] He was accused of extravagant spending in the fort's reconstruction.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The settlement subsequently sparked competition from European Settlers over control of the fur trade in the area.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The fort was used by the Dutch until around 1650 or 1651 when it was decided that it was too far up the river to be of any value.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The buildings and stockades were demolished and Wouter van Twiller assigned Arent Corssen to find a place for another fort.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The British first had a presence in the area in 1634.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] On June 21, 1634, Sir Edmund Ployden was given a charter from King Charles I of England for all territory that lies between New England and Maryland.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] After the Restoration in 1660, previous claims were largely overwritten, the land around Camden was then controlled by different nobles serving under King Charles II that those associated with Sir Edmund Ployden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 1664, the Duke of York had the King Charles II create the new colony for Lord John Berkeley and Sir George Carteret.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] It was named the Province of New Jersey after George Carteret; in 1649, he was Governor of the Isle of Jersey.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Lord John Berkeley kept his share of New Jersey from 1664 until 1674, when he sold it to two Quakers, John Fenwick and Edward Byllynge.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] This due to political difficulties between him, Carteret, and Governor of New York Richard Nicolls, as well as financial difficulties.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Governor Richard Nicolls had objected to the Province of New Jersey as he had exercised control over the area prior under the Province of New York.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] After Edward Byllynge suffered a bankruptcy and having issues with his creditors, William Penn, one of the creditors, was chosen to be arbitrator.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] They argued that he funded the purchase of Lord John Berkeley's share of the Province of New Jersey with funds that were justly due to them.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] It was decided that Fenwick was entitled to 10% of the share, while 90% would be controlled by trustees that are chosen for the benefit of the creditors of Edward Byllynge, who were mostly Quakers themselves.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The trustees were chosen to be William Penn, Gawen Laurie and Nicholas Lucas.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The goal was to have the trustees sell the territory to colonists so that the creditors of Edward Byllynge would be made whole.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] It was also hoped that Quaker may be motivated to emigrate to this territory.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] At the time, the Society of Friends were flirting with the idea of "new country", where they could practice their religious beliefs and not be shamelessly persecuted.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 1676, the Quakers decided to form a colony, spittling the previous colony in two, East Jersey and West Jersey for the Quakers.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Quakers settled in the area at the end of the 17th century and the start of the 18th century, drawn by promises of religious freedom, fairer taxation and more representation in government.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The Quakers expansion, consumption of resources, along with the introduction of alcohol and disease, led to a decline in the Lenape population.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The development of a ferry system along the Delaware River bolstered trade between Fort Nassau and Philadelphia.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Through ferries, families like Coopers and the Kaighns were able to establish settlements in surrounding areas.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 1773, Jacob Cooper played a significant role in developing the area which is today known as Camden, named after Charles Pratt, the Earl of Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Throughout the Revolutionary War, there were several skrimishes and other effects of the war felt by locals.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Development was impeded for the villiage due to the revolution, as Camden was held by the British along with Philadelphia across the Delaware River.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In the 19th century Camden underwent significant changes, transitioning from a hub of transportation to a growing city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden was incorporated as a city on February 13, 1828, from portions of Newton Township, while the area was still part of Gloucester County.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 1832, Camden Township was created as a township coextensive with Camden City.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The township existed until it was repealed in 1848.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden Township was established in 1832 which was the same area as Camden City until it was reduced in 1848.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 1830, the Camden and Amboy Railroad Company was chartered in Camden, which connected ferry terminals from New York City to Philadelphia via rail.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The railroad ended in Camden's Waterfront, where passengers would be ferried across the Delaware River to arrive in Philadelphia.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Similarly to Camden's inception, transportation was a huge catalyst in its growth—the railroads opening in 1834 led to an increase in population and commerce.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] At the turn 20th Century, industry grew rapidly at the hands of companies such as the Victor Talking Machine Company (later RCA Victor), Campbell Soup Company and the New York Shipbuilding Corporation.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] These were major employers in Camden, at times employing tens of thousands in and outside of Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Its location on the Delaware River made it ideal to launch ships.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden also experienced dramatic shifts in its population demographic.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Immigration from Eastern Europe made them the leading ethnic group by 1920, whereas it had previously been German, British, and Irish immigrants.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 1926, a bridge connecting New Jersey and Pennsylvania opened, which was formally named the Benjamin Franklin Bridge in 1956.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The project cost $37 million (equivalent to $673 million in 2025), split evenly between New Jersey and Pennsylvania.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The goal was to reduce ferry traffic between Philadelphia and Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden Central Airport opened in 1929 and was used by several major airlines until Philadelphia International Airport opened in 1939 and brought air service across the Delaware River.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The airport officially closed in April 1957, with a shopping center to be constructed on the 50-acre (20 ha) site.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] During the 1930s, Camden faced economic decline in the face of the Great Depression.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] It was due to Camden's thriving industry that they did not go bankrupt.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The United States role in World War II made the New York Shipbuilding Company the largest and most productive ship yard in the world.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] World War II caused African American migration in and around Camden from the south as there was a need for factory workers for the war effort.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Subsequently, Camden became ethnically and religiously segregated.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] On July 17, 1951, the Delaware River Port Authority, a bi-state agency, was created to promote trade and better coordinate transportation between the two cities of Camden and Philadelphia.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] However, by the 1950s, manufacturing began to slow, causing industries to relocate and employment to dwindle.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In contrast to the growth and industrialization Camden experienced in the early 1900s, there came a drop in population and industry further into the 20th century.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Having reached its peak number of manufacturing jobs in 1950, by 1982 it was a quarter of what it had been.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] After World War II, Campbell's Soup Company and RCA Victor decentralized their production efforts in Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] This Capital Flight was an attempt to avoid an increase in labor wages which unionized workers were fighting for.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The New York Shipbuilding Company, a major contributor of naval units during World War II, shut down in 1967 due to low demand and mismanagement.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] During this period there was a large amount of white flight, in which white residents moved to surrounding suburbs in search of safety and economic opportunity.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Neighborhoods were further divided by the construction of the North-South Freeway; 1,289 families were displaced by the highway, 85% of which were nonwhite families.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Along with this, civil unrest grew resulting in riots.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Police brutality and crime were at an all-time high which further exacerbated Camden's problems.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Efforts to revitalize Camden began in 1980 with Mayor Randy Primas.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In an attempt to generate income for the city, he pursued initiatives such as the construction of a riverfront state-prison and a trash-to-steam incinerator which received substantial opposition from residents.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] With the election of Milton Milan as Camden's next mayor, he declared the city bankrupt, which resulted in $60 million of aid and the state's assumption of Camden's finances.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Another notable revitalization effort was the establishment of non-profit organization, The Parkside Business and Community In Partnership, which occurred in 1993 and is active today.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Redevelopment as an idea has loomed over the city since the 1980s, when Mayor Primas started looking for projects to be able to revitalize with the loss of several foundational industries in the preciding decades.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 2013 the New Jersey Economic Development Authority introduced incentives for companies to relocate to Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Other projects include the redevelopment of the Waterfront, the construction of the Philadelphia 76ers Training Complex, and the Subaru of America's headquarters.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In recent years, Camden has transitioned from a manufacturing industry to an economy focused on education and healthcare.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The Eds-and-Meds Industry has become the largest source of employment in Camden—with institutions such as Cooper University Hospital, Rowan University, Rutgers-Camden, Camden County College, Virtua, Our Lady of Lourdes Medical Center, and CAMcare.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden's role as an industrial city gave rise to distinct neighborhoods and cultural groups that have affected the growth and decline of the city over the course of the 20th century.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden is also home to historic landmarks detailing its rich history in literature, music, social work and industry such as the Walt Whitman House, the Walt Whitman Cultural Arts Center, the Rutgers–Camden Center for the Arts and the Camden Children's Garden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Others include the Camden County Historical Society, which document the city and surrounding area's history.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] It was built in 1899 as a place for those who find anything that links to one's heritage and for other educational purposes.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden's cultural history has been greatly affected by both its economic and social position over the years.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] From 1950 to 1970, industry plummeted, resulting in close to 20,000 jobs being lost for Camden residents.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] This mass unemployment as well as social pressure from neighboring townships caused an exodus of citizens, mostly white.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] This gap was filled by new African American and Latino citizens and led to a restructuring of Camden's communities.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The number of White citizens who left to neighboring towns such as Collingswood or Cherry Hill left both new and old African American and Latino citizens to re-shape their community.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] To help in this process, numerous not-for-profit organizations such as Hopeworks or the Neighborhood Center were formed to facilitate Camden's movement into the 21st century.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The Black Community has been one of the city's foundations since its founding in 1828 and have contributed heavily to the city's culture.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Corinne's Place is a Black-owned soul food restaurant located in Camden, New Jersey.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Corinne Bradley-Powers opened the restaurant on Haddon Avenue in 1989.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The Hispanic and Latino Community in the city has increased heavily in the past twenty years, but have had a long history in Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Puerto Rican Unity for Progress is a multi-service, community-based organization that is located in Camden and serves the Hispanic community who reside in the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The organization was established in 1976 and opened its physical location at 437 Broadway Street in Camden in June 1978.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The Arts and Entertainment have always been presence in the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In the early 20th century, Camden became a hub of music and innovation in entertainment with the presence of the Victor Talking Machine Company (later RCA Victor).
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] It is the birthplace of celebrities such as singers Russ Columbo and Lola Falana.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Today, Camden is home to individuals and groups that help bolster the arts in the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Other congregations that are active now are Newton Monthly Meeting of the Religious Society of Friends on Haddon Avenue and Cooper Street and the Masjid on Mechanic Street.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The first Scientology church was incorporated in December 1953 in Camden by L.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Ron Hubbard, his wife Mary Sue Hubbard, and John Galusha.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Father Michael Doyle, the pastor of Sacred Heart Catholic Church located in South Camden, has played a large role in Camden's spiritual and social history.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 1971, Doyle was part of the Camden 28, a group of anti-Vietnam War activists who planned to raid a draft board office in the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] This is noted by many as the start of Doyle's activities as a radical 'Catholic Left'.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Following these activities, Monsignor Doyle went on to become the pastor of Sacred Heart Church, remaining known for his poetry and activism.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Monsignor Doyle and the Sacred Heart Church's main mission is to form a connection between the primarily white suburban surrounding areas and the inner-city of Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 1982, Father Mark Aita of Holy Name of Camden founded the St.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Aita, a medical doctor and a member of the Society of Jesus, created the first medical system in Camden that did not use rotating primary care physicians.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Luke's has grown to include Patient Education Classes as well as home medical services, aiding over seven thousand Camden residents.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The city has long had a history of philanthropy and charity, dating back to its founding.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The city's founding families were quakers that were very interested in charitable causes like the care of orphans and helping runaway slaves.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] They were members of the Society of Friends whose members were the likes of William Penn.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 1865, the Society of Friends founded the Camden Home for Friendless Children.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Since that home was segregated, the Society of Friends opened the West Jersey Colored Orphanage in 1874.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden has a variety of non-profit Tax-Exempt Organizations aimed to assist city residents with a wide range of health and social services free or reduced charge to residents.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden City, having one of the highest rates of poverty in New Jersey, fueled residents and local organizations to develop organizations aimed to provide relief to its citizens.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] As of the 2000 Census, Camden's income per capita was $9,815.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] This ranking made Camden the poorest city in the state of New Jersey, as well as one of the poorest cities in the United States.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden also has one of the highest rates of childhood poverty in the nation.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] About 45% of employment in Camden is in the "eds and meds" sector, providing educational and medical institutions.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 2018, the city had an average residential property tax bill of $1,710, the lowest in the county, compared to an average bill of $6,644 in Camden County and $8,767 statewide.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Portions of Camden are part of a joint Urban Enterprise Zone.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The city was selected in 1983 as one of the initial group of 10 zones chosen to participate in the program.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In addition to other benefits to encourage employment within the Zone, shoppers can take advantage of a reduced 3.3125% sales tax rate (half of the 6.625% rate charged statewide) at eligible merchants.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Established in September 1988, the city's Urban Enterprise Zone status expires in December 2023.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The UEZ program in Camden and four other original UEZ cities had been allowed to lapse as of January 1, 2017, after Governor Chris Christie, who called the program an "abject failure", vetoed a compromise bill that would have extended the status for two years.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In May 2018, Governor Phil Murphy signed a law that reinstated the program in these five cities and extended the expiration date in other zones.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Census Bureau, the city had a total area of 10.34 square miles (26.78 km2), including 8.92 square miles (23.10 km2) of land and 1.42 square miles (3.68 km2) of water (13.75%).
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden borders Collingswood, Gloucester City, Oaklyn, Pennsauken Township and Woodlynne in Camden County, as well as Philadelphia across the Delaware River in Pennsylvania.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Just offshore of Camden is Pettys Island, which is part of Pennsauken Township.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The Cooper River (popular for boating) flows through Camden, and Newton Creek forms Camden's southern boundary with Gloucester City.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Historically, the Waterfront has always been a foundational part and major hub of the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] It was home to the New York Shipbuilding Company Shipyards until 1968.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Since the 1990s, the Waterfront began a beacon of revitalization for the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The city's waterfront, along the Delaware River is highlighted by its three main attractions, the USS *New Jersey*, the Freedom Mortgage Pavilion, and the Adventure Aquarium.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The waterfront is also the headquarters for Catapult Learning, the Philadelphia 76ers Training Complex, American Water.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden has two generally recognized neighborhoods located on the Delaware River waterfront, Central and South.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] On the Delaware River, with access to the Atlantic Ocean, the Port of Camden handles break bulk, bulk cargo, as well as some containers.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Terminals fall under the auspices of the South Jersey Port Corporation as well as private operators such as Holt Logistics/Holtec International.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The port receives hundreds of ships moving international and domestic cargo annually and is one of the USA's largest shipping centers for wood products, cocoa and perishables.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The most common type of home in Camden is rowhouse, similar to those in the neighboring city of Philadelphia.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Saint Josephs Carpenter Society (SJCS) is a non profit that has rehabilitated 500 homes throughout the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden contains the United States' first federally funded planned community for working class residents, Yorkship Village (now called Fairview).
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The village was designed by Electus Darwin Litchfield, who was influenced by the "garden city" developments popular in England at the time.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 2013, Cherokee Investment Partners had a plan to redevelop north Camden with 5,000 new homes and a shopping center on 450 acres (1.8 km2).
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Cherokee dropped their plans in the face of local opposition and the slumping real estate market.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] They are among several companies receiving New Jersey Economic Development Authority (EDA) tax incentives to relocate jobs in the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden has a humid subtropical climate (*Cfa* in the Köppen climate classification) with hot summers and cool to cold winters.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden's public schools are operated by the Camden City School District.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The district is one of 31 former Abbott districts statewide that were established pursuant to the decision by the New Jersey Supreme Court in *Abbott v.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Burke* which are now referred to as "SDA Districts" based on the requirement for the state to cover all costs for school building and renovation projects in these districts under the supervision of the New Jersey Schools Development Authority.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] As of the 2020–21 school year, the district, composed of 19 schools, had an enrollment of 7,553 students and 668.0 classroom teachers (on an FTE basis), for a student–teacher ratio of 11.3:1.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 2012, The Urban Hope Act was signed into law, allowing renaissance schools to open in Trenton, Newark, and Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The renaissance schools, run by charter companies, differed from charter schools, as they enrolled students based on the surrounding neighborhood, similar to the city school district.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] This makes renaissance schools a hybrid of charter and public schools.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] This is the act that allowed Knowledge Is Power Program (KIPP), Uncommon Schools, and Mastery Schools to open in the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Under the renaissance charter school proposal, the Henry L.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Bonsall Family School became Uncommon Schools Camden Prep Mt.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Ephraim Campus, East Camden Middle School has become part of Mastery Charter Schools, Francis X.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Mc Graw Elementary School and Rafael Cordero Molina Elementary School have become part of the Mastery charter network.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The J.G Whittier Family school has become part of the KIPP Public Charter Schools as KIPP Cooper Norcross Academy.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Students were given the option to stay with the school under their transition or seek other alternatives.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In the 2013–14 school year, Camden city proposed a budget of $72 million to allot to charter schools in the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In previous years, Camden city charter schools have used $52 million and $66 million in the 2012–2013 and 2013–2014 school years, respectively.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] March 9, 2015, marked the first year of the new Camden Charter Schools open enrollment.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Mastery and Uncommon charter schools did not meet enrollment projections for their first year of operation by 15% and 21%, according to Education Law Center.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In October 2016, Governor Chris Christie, Camden Mayor Dana L.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Redd, Camden Public Schools Superintendent Paymon Rouhanifard, and state and local representatives announced a historical $133 million investment of a new Camden High School Project.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The new school is planned to be ready for student occupancy in 2021.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] As of 2019, there are 3,850 Camden students enrolled in one of the city's renaissance schools, with 4,350 Camden students are enrolled one of the city's charter schools.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Combined, these students make up approximately 55% of the 15,000 students in Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Holy Name School, Sacred Heart Grade School, and St.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Joseph Pro-Cathedral School (founded in 1894) are K–8 elementary schools operating under the auspices of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] They operate as four of the five schools in the Catholic Partnership Schools, a post-parochial model of Urban Catholic Education.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The city was once home to two Carnegie libraries, the Main Building and the Cooper Library in Johnson Park.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The city's once extensive library system, beleaguered by financial difficulties, threatened to close at the end of 2010, but was incorporated into the county system.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The main branch closed in February 2011, and was later reopened by the county in the bottom floor of the Paul Robeson Library at Rutgers University.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden also has three academic libraries; The Paul Robeson Library at Rutgers University-Camden serves Rutgers undergraduate and graduate students, as well as students from the Camden campuses of Camden County College and Rowan University.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Rutgers Law School has a law library and Cooper Medical School at Rowan has a medical library.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The Camden Athletic Complex (former site of Campbell's Field) which was completed in 2022. it contains a baseball field, track and field area, soccer field, and lacrosse field.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The Camden Riversharks were an American professional baseball team based in Camden, which played out of the former Campbell's Field.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] An investment totaling $15 million, planned to be split evenly between Rutgers and the city of Camden, will reportedly develop the area into a recreational complex for the city, as well as accommodations for the university's NCAA Division III sports teams.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The team found a property at the Camden Waterfront.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] An $82 million grant was approved by the New Jersey Economic Development Authority to begin construction of the training facility in Camden, and was scheduled to break ground in October 2014.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The grant was somewhat controversial in that it saves the 76ers organization from paying any property taxes or fees that would be accrued by the building over its first decade.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Vocal opponents of the facility claim that the site has now joined a list of large companies or industries that are invited to Camden with significant monetary incentive, at great expense to local tax payers as a form of corporate welfare.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Based on contingent hiring, the grant was to be paid out over 10 years, with the facility scheduled to host practices by 2016.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The training facilities include the two full-size courts, as well as a weight room, full hydrotherapy room, Gatorade Fuel Bar, full players-only restaurant and personal chef, medical facilities, film room, and full locker room.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Since July 1, 1961, the city has operated within the Faulkner Act, formally known as the Optional Municipal Charter Law, under a Mayor-Council form of government.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Since 1994, the city has been divided into four council districts; previously, the entire council was elected at-large.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Elected officials are elected to four-year terms in odd-numbered years, with the mayor and the three at-large seats up for election together and the four ward seats up for vote two years later.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] As of 2026, the Mayor of Camden is Democrat Victor Carstarphen, whose term of office ends December 31, 2029.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Members of the City Council are Council President Angel Fuentes (D, 2029; at large), Vice President Sheila Davis (D, 2029; at large), Arthur Barclay (D, 2027; Ward 1), Christopher R.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Collins (D, 2027; Ward 2), Falio Leyba-Martinez (D, 2027; Ward 3), Jannette Ramos (D, 2027; Ward 4) and Noemi G.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] It was home to the Norcross brothers, three brothers who have dominated Southern Jersey democratic politics for the past 25 years, until legal troubles in 2024 led them to take a backseat.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The city has had its struggles with corruption throughout its political history.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Three Camden mayors have been jailed for corruption: Angelo Errichetti, Arnold Webster, and Milton Milan.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden is located in New Jersey's 1st Congressional District and is part of New Jersey's 5th state legislative district.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] For the 119th United States Congress, New Jersey's 1st congressional district is represented by Donald Norcross (D, Camden).New Jersey is represented in the United States Senate by Democrats Cory Booker (Newark, term ends 2027) and Andy Kim (Moorestown, term ends 2031).
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden County is governed by a Board of County Commissioners composed of seven members chosen at-large in partisan elections for three-year terms on a staggered basis by the residents of the county, with either two or three seats up for election each year as part of the November general election.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] At a reorganization meeting held in January after each election, the newly constituted Board of Commissioners selects one member to serve as Director and another as Deputy Director, each serving a one-year term in that role.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] As of 2025, Camden County's Commissioners are: Commissioner Director Louis Cappelli Jr.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] (D, Collingswood, 2026), Commissioner Deputy Director Edward T.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] McDonnell (D, Pennsauken Township, 2025), Virginia Ruiz Betteridge (D, Runnemede, 2025), Almar Dyer (D, Pennsauken Township, 2027), Melinda Kane (D, Cherry Hill, 2027), Jeffrey L.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Nash (D, Winslow Township, 2027), and Jonathan L.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden County's constitutional officers are: Clerk Pamela Rosen Lampitt (D, Cherry Hill, 2029) Sheriff Chuck Billingham (D, Gloucester City, 2027) and Surrogate Michelle Gentek-Mayer (D, Gloucester Township, 2025).
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden has historically been a stronghold of the Democratic Party.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] As of November 6, 2018, there were 42,264 registered voters in the city of Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] As of March 23, 2011, there were 43,893 registered voters in Camden, of which 17,403 (39.6%) were registered as Democrats, 885 (2.0%) were registered as Republicans and 25,601 (58.3%) were registered as Unaffiliated.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] All Camden mayors since 1935 have been Democrats.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The last Republican Camden mayor was Frederick von Nieda, who only sat in office for a year.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] During his second term, Obama visited Camden in 2015 and said that "Hold you up as a symbol of promise for the nation.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] This city is on to something, no one is suggesting that the job is done," the president said.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] "It's still a work in progress." In the 2012 presidential election, Democrat Barack Obama was seeking reelection and was challenged by Mitt Romney.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The city overwhelmingly voted for Obama in the biggest Democratic landslide in Camden's history.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In the 2016 presidential election, Democrat Hillary Clinton received overwhelming support from the city of Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] On May 11, 2016, Clinton held a rally at Camden County College.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In the 2008 presidential election, Democrat Barack Obama received 91.1% of the vote (22,197 cast), ahead of Republican John McCain, who received around 5.0% (1,213 votes), with 24,374 ballots cast among the city's 46,654 registered voters, for a turnout of 52.2%.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In the 2004 presidential election, Democrat John Kerry received 84.4% of the vote (15,914 ballots cast), outpolling Republican George W.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Bush, who received around 12.6% (2,368 votes), with 18,858 ballots cast among the city's 37,765 registered voters, for a turnout percentage of 49.9.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Officially organized in 1869, the Camden Fire Department (CFD) is the oldest paid fire department in New Jersey and is among the oldest paid fire departments in the United States.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The Camden Fire Department currently operates out of five fire stations, organized into two battalions.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Each battalion is commanded by a battalion chief, who in turn reports to a deputy chief.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The CFD currently operates five engine companies, one squad (rescue-pumper), three ladder companies, and one rescue company, as well as several other special, support, and reserve units.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The department's fireboat is docked on the Delaware River.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Since 2010, the Camden Fire Department has suffered severe economic cutbacks, including company closures and staffing cuts.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] On May 1, 2013, Camden Police Department was disbanded due to a union contract that made it financially impossible to keep officers on the street.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] The Camden County Police Department was formed to succeed the Camden Police Department.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden County's Police Department brought in 25 new officers to train in neighborhoods in hopes they could regain the trust of local communities.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Because of the reorganized force in 2013, the number of cops in the streets has increased, and spread throughout Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden's new police force began patrolling in tandem, speaking with residents, and driving patrol cars.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] A *CNN* report proposed that Camden might be a national model for what police abolition or "defunding the police" could look like.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden once had a national reputation for its violent crime rates, although recent years have seen a significant drop in violent crime, with 2017 seeing the lowest number of homicides in three decades.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Morgan Quitno Press has ranked Camden as one of the top ten most dangerous cities in the United States since 1998, when they first included cities with populations less than 100,000.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Camden was ranked as the third-most dangerous city in 2002, and the most dangerous city overall in 2004 and 2005.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] It improved to the fifth spot for the 2006 and 2007 rankings but rose to number two in 2008 and to the most dangerous spot in 2009.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Morgan Quitno based its rankings on crime statistics reported to the Federal Bureau of Investigation in six categories: murder, rape, robbery, aggravated assault, burglary, and auto theft.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] On October 29, 2012, the FBI announced Camden was ranked first in violent crime per capita of cities with over 50,000 residents.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] There were 23 homicides in Camden in 2017, the lowest since 1987 and almost half as many as the 44 murders the previous year.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Both homicides and non-fatal shootings have declined sharply since 2012, when there were a record 67 homicides in the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 2020, there were, again, 23 homicides reported.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Though 2021 also saw 23 homicides, there was, otherwise, a further reduction in violent crime, contrasting national trends.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] In 2018, the Camden County Police Department reported that violent crime had dropped 18%, led by a 21% decline in aggravated assaults; overall nonviolent crimes fell by 12%, the number of arson incidents fell by 29%, burglaries by 21%, and non-fatal "shooting hit incidents" had dropped by 15%.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Total violent crime in the city declined in 2022, despite 28 murders and a spike of 29% in non-violent crime, highlighted by a sharp increase in car-related crime.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] By 2025, Camden had achieved a milestone of the first summer in 50 years that did not have a murder.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p01] Between 2012 and 2025, homicides in the city of Camden fell 82 percent.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The Walter Rand Transportation Center opened in May 1989 under the name of Camden Transportation Center and was renamed in 1994 for former New Jersey State Senator Walter Rand.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The surface level bus transfer center located on the corner of Martin Luther King Boulevard and Broadway, includes both indoor and outdoor stations and runs between the hours of 6am and 9:30pm, seven days a week.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] A majority of buses that stop at the center are NJ Transit buses that provide inexpensive and quick transportation to Philadelphia, Camden and Burlington Counties surrounding cities.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Depending on distance and route the bus fare varies from under a dollar for closer stops, up to fifty dollars for farther stations including Philadelphia and Atlantic City.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Along with the NJ Transit buses, the center is also home to many Greyhound Lines routes, that provide transportation to neighboring cities as well as to destinations all around the country, with fares varying based on the destination.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Along with the bus stops, the center is home to two rail road system stations, the Walter Rand River Line station and PATCO, Broadway station which provides access to the buses from the surrounding area.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Since opening in March 2004, NJ Transit's River Line has offered light rail service to cities along the Delaware River starting in North Camden, and terminating in Trenton.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] There are four stations located in the city, the southern most station is located at Freedom Mortgage Pavilion located on the Delaware River, and goes north along the river up to Trenton.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The second and third most south stations in Camden stop at the Camden Adventure Aquarium and at Rutgers University.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The last stop in the city, the Walter Rand Transportation Center, located on Martin Luther King Boulevard and Broadway, is a major transportation hub where the PATCO, NJ Transit buses, and Greyhounds all meet.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The PATCO Speedline offers frequent 24-hour train service to Philadelphia and the suburbs to the east in Camden County, including Camden, Collingswood, Haddon Township, Haddonfield, Cherry Hill, Voorhees and Lindenwold.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Throughout the two states there are a total of 13 stations.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Unlike most major US transit systems, the PACTO Speedline is running 24-hours a day.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Opening in 1926 under the name of The Delaware River Bridge Commission, the rail consisted of six stops in Philadelphia stops and two in Camden, City Hall, and Broadway station.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The first station after crossing the river into Philadelphia, Franklin Square closed in 1979 because of the low number of riders.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The station was proposed for a remodel and is planned on opening during the summer of 2024.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The RiverLink Ferry opened March 1992, as a passenger ferry service that crossed the Delaware River connecting the Camden Waterfront with Philadelphia's, Penn's Landing.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The ferry operates daily from May through September, and on Fridays through Sundays in April and October.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Docking at Wiggins Park, located between the Adventure Aquarium and the Battleship New Jersey, the ferry provides access to the Adventure Aquarium, Battleship New Jersey, Camden's Children's Garden, and the Freedom Mortgage Pavilion.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] On the Philadelphia side of the river the ferry docks at the Independence Seaport Museum, and provides access to the many attractions located at Penns Landing, including multiple city piers, and restaurants as well as Museums, the battle ship Olympia, and the submarine Becuna.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Round trip ticket prices range from $8 for children and seniors to $10 for adults while children under the age of four ride for free.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The RiverLink Ferry was not the first ferry to call Camden home.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Since the start of the United States there has been a need to transport goods and people across the Delaware.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Before the construction of the Benjamin Franklin Bridge, there were multiple ferries that launched from Camdens waterfront including on Market street, and Vine street located in the downtown area, as well as Kaighn Avenue located in South Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] During the winter when the river had frozen horse were used to tow the ferries across like sleds, which helped slow the number of injuries and death that occurred from individuals that walked across the ice.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] On one occasion the fire started aboard one of the ferries.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] On March 15, 1856, the Delaware River was full of floating chucks of ice rushing through the rough current when flames burst out along the upper deck.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] People on board did their best to calm the fire with buckets of freezing water but resorted to jumping over board.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] As a result, over sixty people died in the accident with countless missing while only 30 made it out alive.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Between the years of 1727 and 1766 more than 800 slaves were brought by three different ferries and sold in Downtown, Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Today there are historical signs placed at these three sites to commemorate the people sold there.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Route 30 run through Camden to the Benjamin Franklin Bridge on the north side of the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Interstate 76 passes through briefly and interchanges with Interstate 676.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Route 168 passes through briefly in the south and County Routes 537, 543, 551 and 561 all travel through the center of the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Camden has faced many environmental problems due to its history of heavy industry and the improper disposal of contaminants.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Environmental concerns include air/water pollution and soil contamination.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] There are several Superfund sites throughout the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] In recent years, illegal dumping has become an issue due to the large number of vacant lots throughout the city and a lack of security and maintenance.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The Census Bureau's Population Estimates Program calculated a population of 71,100 for 2023, making it the 532nd-most populous municipality in the nation.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] 28.9% of residents were under the age of 18 and 10.3% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] For every 100 females there were 92.0 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 87.7 males age 18 and over.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] There were 24,385 households in Camden, of which 40.1% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Of all households, 21.4% were married-couple households, 22.0% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 47.4% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] About 27.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] There were 27,670 housing units, of which 11.9% were vacant.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.6% and the rental vacancy rate was 7.5%.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The 2010 United States census counted 77,344 people, 24,475 households, and 16,912 families in the city.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] There were 28,358 housing units at an average density of 3,178.7 per square mile (1,227.3/km2).
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 47.04% (36,379) of the population.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The Hispanic population of 36,379 was the tenth-highest of any municipality in New Jersey and the proportion of 47.0% was the state's 16th-highest percentage.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Of the 24,475 households, 37.9% had children under the age of 18; 22.3% were married couples living together; 37.9% had a female householder with no husband present and 30.9% were non-families.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Of all households, 24.8% were made up of individuals and 7.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The average household size was 3.02 and the average family size was 3.56.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] For every 100 females, the population had 94.7 males.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] For every 100 females ages 18 and older there were 91.0 males.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The city of Camden was 47% Hispanic of any race, 44% non-Hispanic black, 6% non-Hispanic white, and 3% other.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] Camden is predominately populated by African Americans and Puerto Ricans.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The Census Bureau's 2006–2010 American Community Survey showed that (in 2010 inflation-adjusted dollars) median household income was $27,027 (with a margin of error of +/− $912) and the median family income was $29,118 (+/− $1,296).
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] About 33.5% of families and 36.1% of the population were below the poverty line, including 50.3% of those under age 18 and 26.2% of those age 65 or over.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] As of 2006, 52% of the city's residents lived in poverty, one of the highest rates in the nation.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The city had a median household income of $18,007, the lowest of all U.S. communities with populations of more than 65,000 residents.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] A group of poor Camden residents were the subject of a *20/20* special on poverty in America broadcast on January 26, 2007, in which Diane Sawyer profiled the lives of three young children growing up in Camden.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] A follow-up was shown on November 9, 2007.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] In 2011, Camden's unemployment rate was 19.6%, compared with 10.6% in Camden County as a whole.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] As of 2009, the unemployment rate in Camden was 19.2%, compared to the 10% overall unemployment rate for Burlington, Camden and Gloucester counties and a rate of 8.4% in Philadelphia and the four surrounding counties in Southeastern Pennsylvania.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The fictional Camden mayor Carmine Polito in the 2013 film *American Hustle* is loosely based on 1970s Camden mayor Angelo Errichetti.
[src:camden-new-jersey/camden-new-jersey-p02] The 1995 film *12 Monkeys* contains scenes on Camden's Admiral Wilson Boulevard.
